04509nam a22006735i 9780823295371DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20221996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1302165294  a97808232953717 a10.1515/97808232953712doi  a(DE-B1597)575379  a(OCoLC)1301549880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360502bisacsh1 aPalladino, Anita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiary of a Yankee Engineer :bThe Civil War Diary of John Henry Westervelt /cAnita Palladino. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (265 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe North's Civil War00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tHistory of the Diary and Drawings of John H. Westervelt -- tChronology -- tJournal of an expedition to Folly Island written by JHW for FSW -- tDiary of an Engineer During the Rebellion -- tEpilogue -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn September 8, 1962, John H. Westervelt enlisted as a private into the 1st New York Volunteer Engineer Corps. That same year, he shipped out of New York on the "Star of the South" to South Carolina to fight for the North in the Civil War. The following April, he began a journal for his 13-year-old son Frazee so that his child could know of his experiences in the war. Sixty-two years later, John Westervelt’s journal – 68 entries written on tattered, yellow pages, a record of "such things as may come under [his] personal observation" – was found in the trash outside his former home now West Farms. In early 1995, his drawings, meant to accompany the written journal, were discovered in the West Point Special Collections Archives. The two have been reunited in Diary of a Yankee Engineer. Westervelt’s words, intended not for the history books but for the education of his young son, present a more humble vision of military life and of the North’s struggle in the Civil War, than the often told sagas of glory. The journal gives us a rare look at the soldier’s life of relentless tedium, the fatiguing fight of brother against brother – of pestilence and illness, giving us a "truer, if not beautiful" picture of war. This is the story of an ordinary man in an extraordinary time – a man who merely lived as he though right and who died in consequence. Anita Palladino’s introduction provides us with a brief history of the man and the events of his life. By salvaging John Westervelt’s journal and reuniting its text with its art, Ms. Palladino has unearthed a rare, firsthand look at the men behind the war of Rebellion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831107432960 cprintz978082321724340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329537140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295371/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK